author: @iliya-malecki
text: Dear Josh Statquest Starmer, please help me to unwrap my brain after it has been wrapped around itself pretty badly. So I've been watching your quantile normalization video, and the message i got is that it's really damn easy, but there is a big but! Distances between each data point are not preserved, obviously, but doesn't it mean we can't use any parametric methods anymore? Like, probability density approximations for each group after this normalization don't mean a thing, so what do we do? Ye i get it we can use rank-based methods, but still, why do we prefer quantile normalization over just moving groups up and down so that their means are equalized, preserving distributions and all that good parametric stuff?
